Anonymous Tue 02 Feb 2021 01:28:54 No.36012293 Report
Quoted By: >>36012619 >>36013088
>>36011873
Movies are a really shitty source for gun knowledge. I'd recommend checking out Forgotten Weapons. While the channel mostly focuses on rare weapons, that's also kind of why it's so good in the first place. Because Ian will almost always show the internal workings of the gun, and he does a good job of explaining how everything works. Looking at all those different guns also gives you a good idea of what makes for a good gun, or a typical gun, for a given era or situation. For instance, why did the French anti-terrorism unit use a sniper revolver? There's a video about that. Why did early revolver development have so many bizarre proprietary cartridges? There's a video about that (several, in fact). Also, it's a good channel to watch. Frankly, a cut far above all other gun channels, and Ian is a real authority on the matter, not some guy with a backyard range.

Other than that, read military stuff. There's another channel (two, actually) by a guy called Mark Felton, and he's a historian who specializes on WWII, mostly Asia. His content is really focused, but this guy writes books about this thing, so you know it's good. You might also want to check out The Great War channel, if that's relevant to you.

But yeah, read military stuff if you want a more detailed knowledge about what military life can be like. Watch documentaries with interviews with veterans, or stuff like Restrepo. The resources you have these days are endless. There's a channel of a Rhodesian veteran and his war stories, and one with interviews with WWII veterans.
